een hints at reduction of flight characteristics at large size,\nwhich is what we'd expect in either a sustained evolutionary trend towards\nflightlessness or an ontogenetic shift towards purely terrestrial locomotion\nin giant individuals.\n\nDelete\n\nReplies\n\nReply\n\nReply\n\n  2. Ivan Kay31 May 2018 at 04:35\n\nGreat post - you do an admirable job on this blog of tackling rather sprawling\ntopics concisely and in a way that is easily digestible. On the maximum mass\nof volant birds, I had thought that Argentavis was supposed to be rather\nheavier than Pelagornis, perhaps 60 + kg rather than 20 - 40 kg? Either way,\nstill a lot smaller than 200 kg.\n\nReplyDelete\n\nReplies\n\n    1. Mark Witton31 May 2018 at 06:25\n\nThanks for the comment, Ivan. The Ksepka study cited above downsized A.\nmagnificens somewhat, predicting wingspans of 5-6 m, with most methods\npredicting a size at the lower end of that range. Masses surpassing 60kg need\nwingspans exceeding 6.5 m or so, but this also requires unrealistically large\nprimary feather lengths for the A. magnificens material. Ksepka did not\nprovide a mass estimate for his downsized A. magnificens (which is fair, the\npaper wasn't about teratorn flight), but a crude wingspan/mass regression\nbased on my own datasets gives a mass of c. 40 kg for a 5.5 m span teratorn.\n\nDelete\n\nReplies\n\nReply\n\n    2. Ivan Kay31 May 2018 at 07:42\n\nThanks for the info, Mark.\n\nDelete\n\nReplies\n\nReply\n\nReply\n\n  3. Hiltrud Cantauw31 May 2018 at 08:27\n\nThank you very much for this interesting article.\n\nReplyDelete\n\nReplies\n\nReply\n\n  4. Jeffrey Lewis31 May 2018 at 09:43\n\nI've got nothing profound or particularly constructive to add. I just wanted\nto share that, as an aerospace engineer with a keen amateur interest in\nevolution (and particularly pterosaurs), these types of technical discussions\nare among my favorite posts you write (though I enjoy practically all of your\nposts). Thanks for taking the time t