\nTheir skeletal mount is proportionally odd (the long torso issue discussed\nabove is a problem again), maybe this factors into their reconstruction. Of\ncourse, until they publish their findings and reconstruction method properly\nwe're just guessing about its validity, but - based on what I know of the\nmaterial, and my experience with pterosaurs generally - I am sceptical of\ntheir proposals.\n\nDelete\n\nReplies\n\nReply\n\n    2. Unknown1 June 2018 at 07:55\n\nThanks, man! It is an honor have my doubt clarified by an authority on the\nmatter.\n\nJust adding:\n\n\\- \"Researchers are not sure whether pterosaurs this size could actually fly.\nAccording to the exhibit\u2019s introductory information there is no conclusive\nevidence to the contrary, but Dracula has a wrist joint that differs greatly\nfrom that of other species that have been found, which could mean it was not\nmeant for flight.\"\n\nSource: https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/meet-dracula-the-largest-\npterosaur-found-to-date/\n\n\\- \"What\u2019s more, the shape of some of the giant creature\u2019s bones, such as\nthose of the shoulder and the wing, suggest it couldn\u2019t fly.\"\n\n\\- \"But that doesn\u2019t necessarily mean members of this species were flightless\nfor their whole lives, Habib says. They may have hatched at or near being\nflight-capable and eventually grew out of it when they reached a size and\nweight that rendered them no longer at risk of predation.\"\n\nSource: https://news.nationalgeographic.com/2018/05/new-species-pterosaur-\nfossil-transylvania-paleontology-science/?beta=true\n\nSome sources comment about joint differences present in these species that\ncould suggest an animal incapable to flying. Let's wait for an official\ndescription of the material.\n\nThanks again!\n\nDelete\n\nReplies\n\nReply\n\nReply\n\n  6. Anonymous31 May 2018 at 14:33\n\nGreat analysis. But why such long necks do you think? Diet? Or something\nrelated to flight? Or a mix of both?\n\nRe