ndlimb soft-tissues show this applies to muscle distributions too, which\nopens the possibility that the ligament system - though probably sharing the\nsame ventrally thickened components as all reptiles (including birds) - might\nhave differed also. We know that reptile hindlimb ligaments can permit some\ndegree of sprawling because, obviously, lizards and crocs can abduct their\nhindlimbs without problem. This implicates that simply having those thick\nventral ligaments is not a barrier to sprawling limbs, and that specifics of\nskeletal and soft-tissue anatomy are the actual controls on hindlimb ROM.\nErgo, we need to understand both these elements in detail to ascertain\npterosaur hindlimb motion and their likely flight pose. The study does not do\nthis however, bringing pterosaurs into the discussion very late in the paper\nand without necessary consideration of their osteological or soft-tissue\ncharacteristics. The resultant discussion is too brief to justify its sweeping\nclaim and, for me, it instead raises numerous, critical questions about its\nmultitude of assumptions and neglected data. A lot of work is needed to\nvalidate the quail-pterosaur analogy, including deepening our understanding of\nsauropsid - and especially pterosaur - soft-tissues and functional morphology.\nUntil this is done, I suggest treating the conclusions of this study with\ncaution.\n\nDelete\n\nReplies\n\nReply\n\nReply\n\n  8. Hiltrud Cantauw1 June 2018 at 00:29\n\nDear Mr. Witton, your comments on the pterosaurs are very interesting. What I\nstill miss is a statement about the type of landing. I wonder if the\npterosaurs at first only put on their hind feet or at the same time with all\nfour feet - or even only with their front legs. Is there an answer to this\nquestion? Or is that still another field of research?\n\nReplyDelete\n\nReplies\n\n    1. Mark Witton1 June 2018 at 01:01\n\nLanding tracks show that pterosaurs landed feet-first, which makes sense: use\nthe wings to maintain lift and slow flight to the point where they can drop\nsafely to the ground. Once down, they drop to all fours to walk away.\n\nDelete\n\nReplies\n\nReply\n\n    2. Hiltrud Cantauw1 June 2018 at 01:16\n\nThank you very much for the quick reply\n\nDelete\n\nReplies\n\nReply\n\nReply\n\n  9. Michael2 June 2018 at 01:34\n\nApropos your mention of Dunning-Kruger, Mark, I have to say I've never heard\nyou claim your expertise in pterosaurs would allow you to safely land an\nAirbus. Would that all showed such wisdom.\n\nReplyDelete\n\nReplies\n\n    1. Pds3.1424 June 2018 at 00:27\n\nTo be fair, he never said he could land a pterasaur either, just that they can\nland themselves, which, coincidentally, is pretty similar to an Airbus!\n\nDelete\n\nReplies\n\nReply\n\nReply\n\n  10. David Marjanovi\u01073 June 2018 at 09:53\n\nBTW, we're living proof that gravity hasn't changed. If it had, second, the\nmoon would either have zoomed off into the distance and left the Earth's axis\nto wobble freely, which it hasn't been doing, or it would have spiraled in and\nkilled us all; first, the Earth would either have zoomed away from the sun or\nspiraled into it.\n\nReplyDelete\n\nReplies\n\n    1. Anonymous15 June 2018 at 04:55\n\nWho suggested that Earth's gravity had changed?\n\nDelete\n\nReplies\n\nReply\n\nReply\n\n  11. Anonymous3 June 2018 at 19:11\n\nGreat article. Just a nitpick but the teratorn Argentavis is estimated to have\ngreatly exceeded 40 kg in mass at around 70 kg. Doesn't undermine your point\nthat pterosaurs grew much larger.\n\nReplyDelete\n\nReplies\n\n    1. Mark Witton4 June 2018 at 03:41\n\nPlease see the comment to Ivan Kay above - this is explained there.\n\nDelete\n\nReplies\n\nReply\n\nReply\n\n  12. Anonymous9 June 2018 at 12:10\n\nMmm. Could birds taking off by quadropedal launch ever grow to pterosaurian\nsizes?\n\nReplyDelete\n\nReplies\n\n    1. Pds3.1424 June 2018 at 00:24\n\nI'm not sure a bird COULD take off quadrupedally. Their limb structure